    "summary": "The Korean Armistice Agreement, signed on July 27, 1953, at Panmunjom, ended active fighting in the [[event:2668|Korean War]] but left the peninsula technically in a state of war, as no peace treaty was ever concluded. The armistice established the Military Demarcation Line close to the 38th parallel — roughly where the war had begun — and created the Demilitarized Zone (DMZ), a 4-kilometer-wide buffer strip that became one of the most heavily fortified borders in the world.\n\nThe agreement took over two years to negotiate, with armistice talks beginning in July 1951 while fighting continued. The most contentious issue was the repatriation of prisoners of war: the North Korean and Chinese side insisted on compulsory repatriation of all prisoners, while the UN Command insisted that prisoners who did not wish to return to communist rule should be allowed to choose their destination. The final agreement provided for voluntary repatriation, and many Chinese and North Korean prisoners chose to go to Taiwan or South Korea rather than return home.\n\nThe armistice froze in place a division of Korea that has persisted for over seven decades. North and South Korea diverged dramatically in political system and economic development: South Korea became a prosperous democracy and major industrial power, while North Korea developed as an isolated and impoverished authoritarian state that pursued nuclear weapons. The absence of a peace treaty has kept the armistice in a perpetual state of provisional instability.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Korean_Armistice_Agreement",
